com.pedroalmir.athena.core.type.container
Class Vector

java.lang.Object
  com.pedroalmir.athena.core.type.container.Vector
All Implemented Interfaces:
VectorMath, java.lang.Iterable<Numeric>, java.util.Collection<Numeric>, java.util.RandomAccess
public class Vector
extends java.lang.Object
implements VectorMath, java.util.RandomAccess, java.util.Collection<Numeric>

Mathematical vector implementation. This class represents a vector within a predefined vector space.

The intention of the class is that instances of the Vector are generally speaking immutable instances. Modifications on the current vector will result in a new instance of the Vector being created and returned. This maintains the mathematical constructs and additionally limits the user to very obvious errors with regard to usage.

If it is required that the Vector be modified to improve performance please consider providing an issue on the tracker, the idea is to create a MutableVector (or something similar) that will accept an instance of Vector and maintain all the modifications internally, without modifying the current instance.

Vector additionally implements a functional interface.

Note: Many methods have been deprecated from previous versions of this class. The applied depreciations have been made to enable a clearer API of usage for the user. All constructors have been deprecated in favor of static factory methods.

Please take note of all depreciations, it influences the usage quite substantially. All depreciations will be removed in a subsequent version.

toArray

public <T> T[] toArray(T[] a)
Returns the array containing all of the elements within this Vector. This method transforms the elements within the Vector to an array representation.

If the provided array is large enough to contain the contents of this Vector, it will be appended to the end of the given array and the same reference that was provided will be returned.

If the given array is, however, smaller than the Vector instance, the contents of the array will be copied to a new array, which will be created internally, with the Vector elements appended directly after the contents of the array. The operation also holds true for arrays of length 0.

toArray(new Object[0]) is identical to the method call toArray().

Specified by:
toArray in interface java.util.Collection<Numeric>
Type Parameters:
T -
Parameters:
a - the input vector.
Returns:
an array representation of the vector.
